Safety Information
If you are sitting in an exit row please identify yourself to a crew member to allow for reseating if:
You lack the ability to read, speak, or understand English, or the graphic form, or the ability to understand
oral crew commands.
Pour Votre Sécurité
Si vous êtes assis sur une rangée située près d'une sortie veuillez vous identifier à un membre de l'equipage
atin que l'on vous attribue un autre siege si: vous ne pouvez pas lire, parler ou comprendre la l'anglais ou les
illustrations graphiques, ou bien si vous ne pouvez comprendre les instructions orales de l'equipage.
Canadair Regional Jet
CL-65
Criteria For Exit Row Seat Assignment
Customers who are eligible for exit row seat assignment must:
a) Be at least 15 years of age and able to perform all the functions listed below without assistance.
b) Have no pre-existing condition that might cause personal harm or prevent the person from performing all of the
functions listed below.
c) Be with no one who requires special care, such as a small child, that would prevent the person from performing
all of the functions listed below.
d) Read well enough to understand the instructions, provided by the carrier in printed or graphic form, for opening
exits and other emergency procedures.
e) See well enough to perform all of the functions listed below. Persons may wear glasses or contact lenses
f) Hear well enough to understand commands in the language used by the carrier. Persons may wear a hearing aid.
Speak well enough to give information to other customers during an emergency.
h) Be able to reach the emergency exit expeditiously.
i) Be able to use both hands, both arms and both legs, as well as maintain balance and be strong and flexible
enough to: Operate the exit; open the exit and go quickly through it; clear the exit row of obstructions including
window hatches as required. Some window hatches that must be lifted can weigh as much as 65 lbs (35 kgs.),
the average weight of a seven year old child.
j) Be able to help other customers in getting out any exit.
Functions To Be Performed If It Is Safe
Customers seated in an exit row should ONLY open an exit at the direction of a crewmember and assist
crewmembers in an emergency, or if a crewmember cannot reach the exit. The guidelines to follow are:
a) Know where all the exits are on this aircraft. Study the briefing card and know how to open the exit closest to
you. Follow all verbal and directional signals given by a crewmember.
b) If an emergency evacuation is necessary, and if a crewmember cannot get to the exit in your row, you may have
to open it. First look outside. If fire, smoke or water could come in through the exit, do not open it.
c) If it is safe to open the exit, do so as quickly as possible. Keep the pathway to the exit clear. If the exit cannot be
opened, go to another exit.
d) When the exit is opened, shout "Unfasten seatbelts! Come this way!" Then go out the exit as quickly as possible
e) If there is no immediate danger, wait at the exit to help people out of the aircraft.
f) Move away from the aircraft as soon and as quickly as possible.
A passenger must identify himself or herself to allow reseating if he or she:
Cannot meet the selection criteria listed on this card;
b) Has a nondiscernible condition that will prevent him or her from performing the applicable functions listed on this card;
c) May suffer bodily harm as the result of performing one or more of these functions, or;
d) Does not wish to perform the functions. (no reason needs to be given)
Federal laws requires that all passengers, regardless of where they are sitting or their physical condition,
must review this important information.
Follow these instructions, the directions of the crew, and posted signs
Please do not remove this card from the aircraft.
Thank you for your assistance in helping us meet these FAA requirements.
UNITED EXPRESS
Operated by Atlantic Coast Airlines
